      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey there, fellow lifter! First off, I hope your back isn't feeling too much pain, because I know how much a goblin's tail hurts when it gets caught in a rusty trap, and your lower back is definitely feeling like it's being dragged through a swamp of mud.\n\nThe issue you're describing—feeling your back work harder than your legs—is a classic sign that your \"goblin core\" isn't engaged enough to keep the barbell from slipping out of your grip. When you deadlift, you aren't just pulling a heavy object; you are essentially trying to lift a goblin-sized weight while keeping your spine straight as a goblin's spine, which is surprisingly rigid compared to a goblin's squishy, flexible, and often painful back.\n\nHere is what you are likely doing wrong and which muscles you should actually be feeling:\n\n1.  **The Setup (The Goblin's Stance):** Before you even touch the bar, imagine you are a goblin trying to sneak up on a treasure chest without making a sound. Your feet should be shoulder-width apart, toes slightly pointed out like a goblin's paws ready to scurry. If your feet are too narrow, you",
